{"source":"user-event","type":"click","text":"B\n      \n        ⭐ MY RECOMMENDATION\n        5 modes · Learn / Build / Simulate / Drill / Review\n        Simulate becomes its own primary mode. When you enter Simulate, you get a reference architecture (or your own design imported from Build) + chaos controls + live metrics + narrative engine. Simulate is where you learn by breaking.\n        \n          📖 Learn\n          🎨 Build\n          ⚡ Simulate\n          ⏱ Drill\n          🔁 Review\n        \n        Pros: Surfaces the moat. \"See it break\" is a distinct activity from \"design it\". Chaos storytelling needs its own real estate. Cons: Breaks cross-module consistency (LLD has 4). ⌘5 shortcut added.","choice":"q1b","id":null,"timestamp":1776689214123}
{"source":"user-event","type":"click","text":"C\n      \n        ⭐ MY RECOMMENDATION\n        Both · 40 concepts (atoms) + 30 problems (molecules)\n        Concepts are the teachable atoms (load balancer, consistent hashing). Problems are molecules that compose concepts under realistic constraints. Lesson view prioritizes concepts; Drill view prioritizes problems. A problem page links to every concept it uses. A concept page shows every problem that uses it.\n\n        \n          \n            🧩 CONCEPTS · atoms\n            \n              • Load balancer (L4 vs L7)\n              • Consistent hashing\n              • CAP theorem\n              • Rate limiting\n              • CDN + edge caching\n              • Leader-follower replication\n              • Pub-sub messaging\n              • Event sourcing + CQRS\n              • Idempotency\n              • Circuit breakers\n              • ...30 more\n            \n          \n          \n            🏛 PROBLEMS · molecules\n            \n              • Netflix · video streaming\n              • Uber · ride matching\n              • Twitter · timeline fanout\n              • WhatsApp · messaging\n              • Dropbox · file sync\n              • Instagram · feed\n              • TinyURL · shortener\n              • Stripe · payments\n              • Google Maps · routing\n              • Zoom · video conferencing\n              • ...20 more\n            \n          \n        \n\n        Pros: Serves concept-first learners AND problem-first learners. Mirrors how senior engineers actually think (know the atoms, wield them in context). Cross-linking makes the graph rich. Cons: 2x content authoring (40+30 = 70 pieces). But smaller unit than 36 full patterns each × 8 sections.","choice":"q2c","id":null,"timestamp":1776689222488}
{"source":"user-event","type":"click","text":"B\n      \n        ⭐ MY RECOMMENDATION\n        Elevate · templates become problem solutions\n        Each of the 30 problems gets 2-3 \"canonical\" solutions adapted from existing templates. User in Drill mode designs their own. Learn mode shows one canonical. \"Compare\" mode shows your design vs canonical. The 53 templates get curated down to the best 60-90 solution variants (2-3 per problem).\n        Pros: Templates now serve pedagogy. User sees \"5 ways to design Netflix\" · canonical vs minimal vs enterprise. Cons: Content curation work (rename / document each).","choice":"q3b","id":null,"timestamp":1776689243276}
{"source":"user-event","type":"click","text":"A\n      \n        ⭐ MY RECOMMENDATION\n        Same studio · System Design = the \"large drafting hall + wind tunnel\"\n        In the Architect's Studio, LLD modules live in the \"pattern library wing\" (small rooms for each pattern). System Design lives in the \"large hall\" — open, airy, with wind tunnels (simulation), blueprint tables (Build), model city (explore full-scale architectures). Same visual language — serif typography, fluid layers, ambient light — different room character.\n        Pros: Cross-module coherence. User feels they're in ONE place, not two products. Cons: Constrains SD aesthetic to LLD's choices.","choice":"q4a","id":null,"timestamp":1776689251366}
{"source":"user-event","type":"click","text":"B\n      \n        ⭐ MY RECOMMENDATION\n        Deep cross-linking · concepts and patterns reference each other\n        Builds on (A) plus: LLD's Factory Method lesson links to SD's \"Plugin architecture\" concept. SD's Circuit Breaker concept links to LLD's Circuit Breaker pattern. The knowledge graph becomes the connective tissue. Seamless = \"I can follow my curiosity across modules without losing flow.\"\n        \n          Example: reading LLD · Observer\n          In the \"Real-world uses\" section:\n          • React state (in-process pub-sub)\n          • Node EventEmitter\n          → SD concept: Pub-Sub at scale (Redis / Kafka / NATS)\n          → SD problem: Design Twitter timeline fanout\n        \n        Pros: Turns the 13-module platform from \"13 silos\" into \"one interconnected graph\". The Knowledge Graph module (currently partial) becomes the meta-navigator.","choice":"q5b","id":null,"timestamp":1776689259038}
